{
  "title": "Binary System",
  "sections": [
    {
      "type": "section",
      "title": "Binary: The Language of Computers",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "image",
          "imageKey": "binary_digits",
          "alt": "Binary digits",
          "caption": "Binary digits: only 0 and 1",
          "optimized": true,
          "scalePercent": 50
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Binary uses only two symbols: 0 and 1. These map naturally to electronic circuits that can be OFF (0) or ON (1)."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "ordered": false,
          "items": [
            "0 represents OFF – no current",
            "1 represents ON – current flowing"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Each position in a binary number represents a power of 2, just like decimal uses powers of 10."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "section",
      "title": "How Binary Works",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Just like decimal uses powers of 10, binary uses powers of 2. Each position represents a power of 2."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "title": "Binary Place Values",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "code",
              "language": "text",
              "code": "Position:  8  4  2  1  (powers of 2)\nBinary:    1  0  1  1\nDecimal:   8+ 0+ 2+ 1 = 11"
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "So binary 1011 equals decimal 11"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 3,
          "text": "Converting Decimal to Binary"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "To convert decimal to binary, repeatedly divide by 2 and track remainders:"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "title": "Convert 13 to Binary",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "code",
              "language": "text",
              "code": "13 ÷ 2 = 6 remainder 1\n 6 ÷ 2 = 3 remainder 0\n 3 ÷ 2 = 1 remainder 1\n 1 ÷ 2 = 0 remainder 1\n\nRead remainders bottom to top: 1101\nSo 13 in decimal = 1101 in binary"
            }
          ]
        },
